{
  "Convert 120 degrees to radians.": "",
  "pi/3": "",
  "pi/6": "",
  "3pi/4": "",
  "2pi/3": "",
  "To convert degrees to radians, multiply by pi/180: 120 * pi/180 = 120pi/180 = 2pi/3.": "",
  "Convert pi/4 radians to degrees.": "",
  "30 degrees": "",
  "90 degrees": "",
  "45 degrees": "",
  "60 degrees": "",
  "To convert radians to degrees, multiply by 180/pi: (pi/4) * (180/pi) = 180/4 = 45 degrees.": "",
  "An angle of 270 degrees is in which quadrant (or on which axis)?": "",
  "Negative y-axis": "",
  "Quadrant IV": "",
  "Quadrant III": "",
  "Positive x-axis": "",
  "An angle of 270 degrees places the terminal side on the negative y-axis (pointing straight down). It is a quadrantal angle, lying on the boundary between Quadrants III and IV.": "",
  "What is the reference angle for 225 degrees?": "",
  "225 degrees": "",
  "135 degrees": "",
  "225 degrees is in Quadrant III. The reference angle is 225 - 180 = 45 degrees. The reference angle is always the acute angle formed between the terminal side and the x-axis.": "",
  "What is the measure of one complete revolution in radians?": "",
  "pi/2": "",
  "pi": "",
  "2pi": "",
  "4pi": "",
  "One complete revolution equals 360 degrees, which is equivalent to 2pi radians. This is the fundamental relationship between the degree and radian systems.": "",
  "Find a positive coterminal angle for -60 degrees.": "",
  "300 degrees": "",
  "240 degrees": "",
  "120 degrees": "",
  "To find a positive coterminal angle, add 360 degrees: -60 + 360 = 300 degrees. Coterminal angles share the same terminal side.": "",
  "Convert 315 degrees to radians.": "",
  "7pi/6": "",
  "5pi/4": "",
  "7pi/4": "",
  "3pi/2": "",
  "315 * pi/180 = 315pi/180 = 7pi/4. This angle is in Quadrant IV, 45 degrees short of a full revolution.": "",
  "What is the reference angle for 150 degrees?": "",
  "150 degrees": "",
  "150 degrees is in Quadrant II. The reference angle is 180 - 150 = 30 degrees. Reference angles are always positive and acute (between 0 and 90 degrees).": "",
  "An arc of a circle with radius 6 cm subtends a central angle of pi/3 radians. What is the arc length?": "",
  "2pi cm": "",
  "3pi cm": "",
  "pi cm": "",
  "6pi cm": "",
  "Arc length = radius * angle in radians = 6 * pi/3 = 6pi/3 = 2pi cm. The formula s = r * theta gives the arc length directly when the angle is in radians.": "",
  "In which quadrant does a 200-degree angle terminate?": "",
  "Quadrant I": "",
  "Quadrant II": "",
  "An angle of 200 degrees is between 180 and 270 degrees, which places its terminal side in Quadrant III. In Quadrant III, both sine and cosine are negative.": "",
  "What is a radian?": "",
  "The angle formed by two perpendicular lines": "",
  "One-360th of a complete revolution": "",
  "The angle subtended at the center of a circle by an arc equal in length to the radius": "",
  "Half of a degree": "",
  "A radian is defined as the central angle subtended by an arc whose length equals the radius of the circle. One full revolution equals 2pi radians (approximately 6.28 radians).": "",
  "What is standard position for an angle?": "",
  "An angle with its vertex at the center of a circle": "",
  "Any angle less than 90 degrees": "",
  "An angle with its vertex at the origin and initial side along the positive x-axis": "",
  "An angle measured clockwise from the y-axis": "",
  "An angle is in standard position when its vertex is at the origin of the coordinate plane and its initial side lies along the positive x-axis. The terminal side rotates counterclockwise for positive angles.": "",
  "What are coterminal angles?": "",
  "Angles that add up to 90 degrees": "",
  "Angles that add up to 180 degrees": "",
  "Angles that are always positive": "",
  "Angles that share the same terminal side when drawn in standard position": "",
  "Coterminal angles share the same terminal side when drawn in standard position. They differ by multiples of 360 degrees (or 2pi radians). For example, 30 degrees and 390 degrees are coterminal.": "",
  "What is a reference angle?": "",
  "The angle measured from the y-axis": "",
  "The negative version of the original angle": "",
  "The supplement of the original angle": "",
  "The acute angle formed between the terminal side of an angle and the x-axis": "",
  "A reference angle is the positive acute angle formed between the terminal side of an angle in standard position and the nearest part of the x-axis. It is always between 0 and 90 degrees.": "",
  "What does the term 'initial side' mean when describing an angle in standard position?": "",
  "The shortest side of a triangle": "",
  "The ray along the positive x-axis from which the angle is measured": "",
  "The ray that rotates to form the angle": "",
  "The y-axis": "",
  "The initial side is the fixed ray along the positive x-axis from which an angle in standard position is measured. The other ray, which rotates to create the angle, is called the terminal side.": "",
  "What does 'terminal side' mean in the context of angles?": "",
  "The vertical axis of the coordinate plane": "",
  "The hypotenuse of a right triangle": "",
  "The ray that rotates from the initial side to form the angle": "",
  "The fixed ray along the positive x-axis": "",
  "The terminal side is the ray that rotates from the initial side to form the angle. Its position determines which quadrant the angle falls in and the sign of trigonometric functions.": "",
  "What is a quadrantal angle?": "",
  "Any angle less than 360 degrees": "",
  "An angle in Quadrant I only": "",
  "An angle that measures exactly 45 degrees": "",
  "An angle whose terminal side lies on one of the coordinate axes": "",
  "A quadrantal angle is an angle in standard position whose terminal side lies on one of the coordinate axes (x or y). Examples include 0, 90, 180, 270, and 360 degrees.": "",
  "What does 'arc length' mean?": "",
  "The diameter of the circle": "",
  "The distance along a curved section of a circle between two points": "",
  "The straight-line distance between two points on a circle": "",
  "The area of a sector": "",
  "Arc length is the distance measured along the curved portion of a circle between two points. It is calculated using s = r * theta, where r is the radius and theta is the central angle in radians.": "",
  "What does the term 'degree' mean as a unit of angle measure?": "",
  "One-360th of a full rotation": "",
  "The length of an arc equal to the radius": "",
  "One-100th of a full rotation": "",
  "The area of a circle divided by pi": "",
  "A degree is a unit of angle measurement equal to 1/360th of a full rotation. A complete circle measures 360 degrees. This system dates back to ancient Babylonian mathematics.": "",
  "What does 'sector area' mean?": "",
  "The perimeter of a circular region": "",
  "The total area of the circle": "",
  "The area of the pie-shaped region enclosed by two radii and an arc of a circle": "",
  "The length of the arc": "",
  "Sector area is the area of a pie-shaped region bounded by two radii and the arc between them. It is calculated as A = (1/2) * r^2 * theta, where theta is in radians.": "",
  "A Ferris wheel has a radius of 25 meters and rotates through an angle of 2pi/3 radians. What distance does a rider travel along the wheel during this rotation?": "",
  "50pi/3 meters": "",
  "25pi/3 meters": "",
  "75pi meters": "",
  "50 meters": "",
  "Arc length s = r * theta = 25 * (2pi/3) = 50pi/3 meters, which is approximately 52.4 meters. The rider travels along the arc of the circle as the wheel rotates.": "",
  "A sprinkler rotates through an angle of 150 degrees and sprays water 10 feet. What is the area of the sector being watered?": "",
  "50pi square feet": "",
  "75pi square feet": "",
  "125pi/3 square feet": "",
  "100pi/3 square feet": "",
  "First convert 150 degrees to radians: 150 * pi/180 = 5pi/6. Sector area = (1/2) * r^2 * theta = (1/2)(10^2)(5pi/6) = (1/2)(100)(5pi/6) = 500pi/12 = 125pi/3 square feet.": "",
  "A clock's minute hand is 12 inches long. How far does the tip of the minute hand travel in 20 minutes?": "",
  "4pi inches": "",
  "8pi inches": "",
  "24pi inches": "",
  "12pi inches": "",
  "In 20 minutes, the minute hand sweeps 20/60 = 1/3 of a full revolution = (1/3)(2pi) = 2pi/3 radians. Arc length = r * theta = 12 * (2pi/3) = 24pi/3 = 8pi inches.": "",
  "A pizza is cut into 8 equal slices. What is the central angle of each slice in radians?": "",
  "pi/8": "",
  "pi/4": "",
  "A full pizza is 2pi radians. Dividing into 8 equal slices: 2pi / 8 = pi/4 radians per slice, which equals 45 degrees.": "",
